The '''khirqa''' is the initiatory cloak of the [[Sufi]] chain of spirituality, with which [[esoteric]] knowledge and [[barakah]] is passed from the [[Murshid]] or the [[Sheikh|Shaikh]] to the aspirant [[murid]]. The khirqa initiates an aspirant into the [[silsilah]], the chain or lineage of sheikhs that goes back to the Islamic prophet, [[Muhammad]]. This chain serves as the channel through which barakah flows from the source of spiritual revelation to the being of the initiate.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hoffman|first=Valerie|title=Sufism, Mysticism, and Saints in Modern Egypt|year=1995|publisher=University of South Carolina Press|location=Columbia}}</ref>

==Subdivisions==
There are two kinds of this kind of transmission (tanakkul) of barakah through the khirqa: khirqa-yi irada and khirqa-yi tabarruk.  Khirqa-yi irada is characterized by the passing of barakah to the aspirant from the singular sheikh to which he or she has pledged allegiance ([[bay'at]]).  Khirqa-yi tabarruk, also known as the "frock of blessing", is characterized by the passing of barakah to the worthy aspirant from any sheikh that he or she has encountered.<ref>{{cite book|last=Schimmel|first=Annemarie|title=Mystical Dimensions of Islam|year=1975|publisher=The University of North Carolina Press|location=Chapel Hill}}</ref>  
The silsilah chain created from the passing of the khirqa that confirms authenticity of many [[hadith]]s is a form of [[isnad]].  It was not until the late eleventh and twelfth centuries that [[Sufism]] accepted this form of [[isnad]] as a means to transmit mystical knowledge and blessings.<ref>{{cite book|last=Brown|first=Jonathan|title=Hadith: Muhammad's Legacy in the Medieval and Modern World|year=2009|publisher=Oneworld Publications|location=Oxford}}</ref>

