{{Infobox book | name = Kierkegaardian Studies | title_orig = Études kierkegaardiennes | translator = | image = Études kierkegaardiennes.gif | caption = Book cover to Études kierkegaardiennes | author = [[Jean Wahl]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = France | language = French | series = | subject = Philosophy | publisher = | release_date = 1938 | english_release_date = | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover|Hardback]]) | pages = | isbn = | dewey= | congress= | oclc= | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''Kierkegaardian Studies''''' ({{lang-fr|Études kierkegaardiennes}}) is a 1938 book about [[Søren Kierkegaard]] by philosopher [[Jean Wahl]]. Its publication marked a significant turning-point in [[French philosophy]], which formally introduced and disseminated Kierkegaard's philosophy to France.<ref name=Stewart>{{cite book | last = Stewart | first = John | title = Kierkegaard and Existentialism | publisher = Ashgate Publishing | location = Farnham | year = 2007 | isbn = 9781409426417 |pages=397–400}}</ref> ''Kierkegaardian Studies'' was one of the first French studies of Kierkegaard to treat him as a coherent philosopher and theologian, and raised questions that became central to Kierkegaard studies and to [[Existentialism]] in general.<ref name=Stewart/> Before Wahl's book, very few people in France knew much about Kierkegaard. After it, almost every French intellectual did.<ref name=Stewart2>{{cite book | last = Stewart | first = John | title = Kierkegaard and Existentialism | publisher = Ashgate Publishing | location = Farnham | year = 2007 | isbn = 9781409426417 |page=397}}</ref>
