{{ Infobox scientist | name = Stephen K. White | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = 1949 | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = [[United States|American]] | ethnicity = | fields = [[Political philosophy|Political theory]] | workplaces = [[University of Virginia]] | alma_mater = [[City University of New York]] | doctoral_advisor = | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | influences = | influenced = | awards = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | footnotes = }}
'''Stephen K. White''' (born 1949),<ref name=Congress>{{cite web |title= White, Stephen K. |url= http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n86121266.html | publisher= Library of Congress |accessdate= 21 July 2014 |quote= CIP t.p. (Stephen K. White) data sheet (b. 1949) }}</ref> is James Hart Professor of Politics at the [[University of Virginia]]. His research focuses on [[Critical theory|critical]] [[Social theory|social]] and [[political theory]], [[philosophy of social science]], and [[Continental philosophy|continental]] political thought. He has contributed to several scholarly works on [[Jürgen Habermas]], including ''The Cambridge Companion to Habermas'', which he edited.<ref name=Habermas>{{cite book | last = White | first = Stephen | title = The recent work of Jürgen Habermas: reason, justice and modernity | publisher = Cambridge University Press | location = Cambridge England New York | year = 1989 | isbn = 9780521389594 }}</ref> He is also a past editor of the journal ''[[Political Theory (journal)|Political Theory]]''.
Recently, White's research has focused upon the concept of [[weak ontology]], which he uses to describe a non-[[Foundationalism|foundationalist]] approach to [[normative affirmation]]{{huh|date=January 2018}} extrapolated from the works of [[George Kateb]], [[Charles Taylor (philosopher)|Charles Taylor]], [[Judith Butler]], and [[William E. Connolly]].
== Education == White received his Ph.D. from the [[City University of New York]] in 1980.
